[2026-01-22 00:30:34] [INFO] Full LLM response:
The Erdős Problem 153 asks whether the minimum of the normalized sum of squares of gaps in the sum set $A+A$ of a Sidon set $A$ of size $n$, denoted here by $f(n)$, tends to infinity as $n \to \infty$.

For a Sidon set $A \subseteq [1, N]$ with $|A|=n$, it is known that $N \gtrsim n^2$. The sum set $A+A$ has size $m = n(n+1)/2 \asymp n^2/2$ and is contained in $[2, 2N]$. The range of $A+A$ is roughly $2n^2$. The sum of squares of differences $\sum (s_i - s_{i-1})^2$ is minimized when the differences are uniform. The average difference is roughly $2N/m \approx 4$. Thus, $\sum (s_i - s_{i-1})^2 \gtrsim m \cdot 4^2 \approx 8n^2$.
The function $f(n)$ is defined as this sum divided by $n$, so $f(n) \gtrsim 8n^2/n = 8n$.
Since $8n \to \infty$, we expect `Tendsto f atTop atTop` to be true.
