The problem asks whether `f n`, defined as the minimum of the normalized sum of squared differences of the sumset elements of a Sidon set of size `n`, tends to infinity as `n` tends to infinity.

Let $A$ be a Sidon set of size $n$. The sumset $S = A + A$ has size $|S| = \binom{n+1}{2} = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}$. Let the elements of $S$ be $s_0 < s_1 < \dots < s_{|S|-1}$. The quantity of interest is $\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{|S|-1} (s_i - s_{i-1})^2$.
Since $s_i$ are distinct integers, $s_i - s_{i-1} \ge 1$, which implies $(s_i - s_{i-1})^2 \ge 1$.
Thus, $\sum (s_i - s_{i-1})^2 \ge \sum 1 = |S| - 1 = \frac{n(n+1)}{2} - 1$.
Dividing by $n$, we get $f(n) \ge \frac{n^2+n-2}{2n} \approx \frac{n}{2}$.
Since $\frac{n}{2} \to \infty$, the limit is $\infty$.
The answer to the question "Must lim f n = ∞?" is Yes.

