The problem asks whether the sequence of minimum normalized sums of squared gaps of sumsets of Sidon sets of size $n$, denoted by $f(n)$, tends to infinity as $n \to \infty$.

For a Sidon set $A$ of size $n$, the sumset $A+A$ consists of sums $a+b$ with $a, b \in A$. The Sidon property implies that all sums $a+b$ with $a \le b$ are distinct. The number of such pairs is $\binom{n}{2} + n = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}$. Thus, the cardinality of the sumset $S = A+A$ is $|S| = \frac{n(n+1)}{2}$.
Let $s_0 < s_1 < \dots < s_{|S|-1}$ be the elements of $S$. The sum in the definition of $f(n)$ is $\sum_{i=1}^{|S|-1} (s_i - s_{i-1})^2$.
Since $s_i$ are distinct integers, $s_i - s_{i-1} \ge 1$, so $(s_i - s_{i-1})^2 \ge s_i - s_{i-1}$.
Therefore, $\sum (s_i - s_{i-1})^2 \ge \sum (s_i - s_{i-1}) = s_{|S|-1} - s_0$.
